\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Operational Boundaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To ensure clarity of mission and resource allocation,
 the following boundaries are established:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Business Ownership
\series default
:
 The Requesting Department shall serve as Project Lead and shall manage scope,
 timelines,
 acceptance,
 and invoicing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Technical Enablement
\series default
:
 Information Operations shall provide security validation,
 network connectivity,
 and infrastructure provisioning necessary to support approved engagements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Prohibition
\series default
:
 Information Operations shall not serve as Project Manager for third-party engagements initiated by other departments,
 and departments shall not delegate contract ownership or business-logic decisions to IT personnel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Supply Chain Risk Management (SCRM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Elko County shall assess and manage risk associated with the Information and Communications Technology (ICT) supply chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Vendor Risk Assessment
\series default
:
 All new technology vendors shall undergo a risk assessment prior to contract execution commensurate with service criticality and data classification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Prohibited Technologies (NDAA §889 / Federal Funding Integrity)
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Elko County shall not procure,
 renew,
 or expand deployment of equipment or services identified as “covered” under applicable federal restrictions,
 including items appearing on the FCC Covered List,
 to preserve eligibility for federal funding and reduce supply chain exposure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Information Operations shall identify discovered covered equipment and shall require segregation and replacement planning based on risk and lifecycle constraints.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Enhanced Due Diligence
\series default
:
 For high-impact vendors,
 Information Operations may require independent attestations (e.g.,
 SOC reports),
 security questionnaires,
 or other evidence of control effectiveness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Contracting and Pre-Engagement Controls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
No Contract,
 No Access
\series default
:
 No third-party logical access shall be granted,
 and no vendor hardware shall be installed or connected,
 until a contract or formal agreement is fully executed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Data Protection Addendum
\series default
:
 Contracts involving Confidential or Restricted data (per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
) shall incorporate County-required security and data protection terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS Mandate
\series default
:
 Any vendor with potential logical access to CJI,
 or unescorted access to physically secure locations where CJI is processed,
 shall execute the CJIS Security Addendum (Appendix H) and comply with CJIS contractor oversight requirements,
 including acknowledgments retained for audit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS Contractor Certifications
\series default
:
 The contracting agency shall ensure each contractor employee with CJI access is provided a copy of the CJIS Security Addendum and CJIS Security Policy,
 executes the CJIS Security Addendum Certification,
 and that executed certifications are retained and available for audit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS External Provider Oversight
\series default
:
 For vendors providing external system services with access to CJI,
 agreements shall provide the CSA/CSO (and their designated auditors,
 including County representatives as authorized) authority to conduct audits (at minimum triennially) and unannounced security inspections,
 and to require evidence of control compliance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Fingerprinting
\series default
:
 Prior to granting logical or unescorted physical access to CJI,
 all vendor personnel shall undergo a state of residency and national fingerprint-based record check,
 adjudicated by the CSA/SIB,
 in accordance with CJIS Security Policy 5.12.1.1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Notification and Cooperation
\series default
:
 Agreements shall require vendors to notify Information Operations immediately of any suspected or confirmed incident affecting County systems or County data.
 If CJI may be impacted,
 vendor notification shall occur immediately and no later than one (1) hour after discovery,
 to support mandatory CJIS reporting timelines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monitoring and Service Oversight
\series default
:
 Contracts shall support County monitoring,
 review,
 and sufficient visibility into security aspects of the provided services,
 consistent with CJIS monitoring expectations where applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Asset Integration,
 Inventory,
 and Tagging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
County-Owned Technology:
 Vendor-provided or vendor-installed hardware that is owned wholly by the County,
 or is tagged and treated as County-governed / IO-managed technology under County custody for the duration of its deployment,
 and becomes part of County infrastructure shall be tagged and governed in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Leased Infrastructure Equipment (GREEN Tags)
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Leased or rented devices that connect to County networks (e.g.,
 copiers/MFPs) shall be tagged with GREEN County asset tags and treated as County-governed / IO-managed technology under County custody for the duration of service.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
GREEN Tag Governance
\series default
:
 GREEN tags indicate Information Operations technical administration,
 configuration control,
 and lifecycle governance for the duration of deployment;
 contractual ownership and vendor maintenance obligations remain defined by the lease/SLA.
 For purposes of 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 “procured” includes leased acquisitions when Information Operations exercises configuration control and lifecycle governance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Such devices shall be recorded in the Configuration Management Database (CMDB) as distinct configuration items,
 referencing lease/contract identifiers,
 to support lifecycle control and decommission verification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Prior to return,
 devices shall undergo data sanitization appropriate to stored data/media in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and 
\series bold
NIST SP 800-88
\series default
 guidance.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Enforcement
\series default
:
 Assets not tagged (where applicable) or not recorded in the Asset Inventory/CMDB shall be denied network connectivity and technical support.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Contractor Equipment and Support Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Default Requirement
\series default
:
 Contractors shall provide their own equipment unless an exception is approved in writing by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
BYOD (Zero Support Model)
\series default
:
 Information Operations shall not troubleshoot,
 configure,
 or install software on non-County devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Network Admission Enforcement
\series default
:
 Information Operations may deny connectivity to contractor devices that do not meet County security requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 System and Network Access Control
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Least Privilege
\series default
:
 Third-party access shall be explicitly authorized,
 time-bounded where feasible,
 and limited to least privilege required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Named Accounts Only
\series default
:
 Generic/shared vendor accounts are prohibited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Remote Access
\series default
:
 Vendors shall use County-approved secure remote access (VPN + MFA).
 Persistent,
 unmonitored tunnels are prohibited unless explicitly authorized by the IT Director for critical support.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Logging and Monitoring
\series default
:
 Vendor activity shall be logged and monitored in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Data Sovereignty and Protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Non-CJI Data Residency
\series default
:
 County data (excluding CJI) stored or processed by third-party cloud providers shall reside within the continental United States unless an exception is approved through the exception process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJI Sovereignty
\series default
:
 Criminal Justice Information (CJI) shall comply with Policy 1.11 CJI Data Sovereignty requirements.
 Where requirements conflict,
 CJI sovereignty requirements shall govern.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Data Ownership
\series default
:
 County data remains the property of Elko County.
 Vendors acquire no rights beyond contractually authorized use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.8 Termination and Offboarding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Upon contract termination or project completion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Immediate Revocation
\series default
:
 The Requesting Department shall notify Information Operations within 24 hours;
 Information Operations shall disable logical access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Asset Reclamation
\series default
:
 County-issued assets shall be returned within three (3) business days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Data Return/Destruction
\series default
:
 Vendors shall certify return or secure destruction of County data consistent with County sanitization standards.
\end_layout

